---
import data from '../data/fatalities.json';

const sources = data.sources;
const waymo = data.waymoSafety;
---

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Methodology &amp; Sources</h2>
    <p class="section-subtitle">Full transparency on data, assumptions, and limitations</p>

    <div class="methodology-content">
      <h3>How the counter works</h3>
      <p>
        The live counter estimates preventable deaths by interpolating Seattle's cumulative
        traffic fatalities since January 1, 2023 (the first legislative session after
        <a href="https://app.leg.wa.gov/rcw/default.aspx?cite=46.92&full=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RCW 46.92</a>
        took effect, which established AV testing but provided no pathway to commercial deployment)
        and applying Waymo's peer-reviewed safety reduction factor.
      </p>
      <p>
        Seattle fatality data comes from
        <a href="https://www.seattle.gov/transportation/projects-and-programs/safety-first/vision-zero" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SDOT Vision Zero</a>
        crash reports: 2023 (27 deaths), 2024 (29 deaths), 2025 (25 deaths),
        2026 (25, projected at 2025 rate). Deaths are interpolated linearly within
        each year to produce a real-time estimate.
      </p>

      <h3>Estimate methodology</h3>
      <p>
        The headline figure applies an 85% any-injury-reported crash reduction to 5%
        of vehicle miles traveled. The 85% comes from
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/15389588.2024.2380786" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kusano et al. (2024)</a>,
        which analyzed 7.1M rider-only miles. A subsequent
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/15389588.2025.2499887" target="_blank" rel="noopener">2025 study</a>
        covering 56.7M miles found a 79% reduction in any-injury-reported crashes (95% CI: 71–85%)
        and 85% fewer suspected serious injury+ crashes (95% CI: 39–99%).
      </p>
      <p>
        The 5% VMT share is a conservative proxy for AV ride-hail market share.
        Ride-hail currently accounts for ~2% of Seattle metro VMT
        (<a href="https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-study-finds-over-97-of-vehicle-miles-traveled-in-major-us-cities-are-completed-by-personal-and-commercial-vehicles-300896095.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fehr &amp; Peers, 2019</a>)
        — the lowest of six major cities studied. The 5% figure assumes AV ride-hail
        captures the urban-core market and grows significantly, as it has in cities
        like San Francisco (~13% of city-core VMT).
      </p>

      <h3>Key assumptions &amp; limitations</h3>
      <ul class="assumptions-list">
        <li>
          The 85% reduction comes from Kusano et al.'s analysis of {waymo.milesAnalyzed}
          autonomous miles in Phoenix and San Francisco. Real-world deployment
          in Seattle could differ.
        </li>
        <li>
          Fatality reductions are extrapolated from injury crash data. Fatality-specific
          reductions may be higher or lower than the overall injury crash reduction.
        </li>
        <li>
          The 5% VMT share is speculative. Seattle metro ride-hail is currently ~2%
          of total VMT (Fehr &amp; Peers, 2019). City-core share would be higher,
          but 5% still assumes substantial growth beyond current ride-hail levels.
          For context, San Francisco's ride-hail VMT share is ~13%.
        </li>
        <li>
          The "delay" framing is debatable. Unlike DC, where a mandated study deadline
          was missed, Washington's situation is a legislative gap — the state passed
          a testing law but never created a commercial deployment framework. Reasonable
          people can disagree about when the delay "started."
        </li>
        <li>
          Seattle's hilly terrain, frequent rain, and specific road conditions differ
          from Waymo's primary operating environments (Phoenix, San Francisco).
          Waymo has been testing in Seattle since Sep 2025 partly to address this.
        </li>
        <li>
          Cause-of-crash percentages (impaired, speed, distraction) are Washington
          state-level figures from
          <a href="https://wtsc.wa.gov/wtsc-2023-traffic-fatalities/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WTSC</a>,
          not Seattle-specific. These categories can overlap (a crash may involve both
          impairment and speeding).
        </li>
        <li>
          These figures represent potential lives saved, not certainties. AV technology
          continues to improve, and real-world results will depend on deployment specifics.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Data sources</h3>
      <ul>
        {sources.map(source => (
          <li>
            <a href={source.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{source.name}</a>
            <span>{source.description}</span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <div class="disclaimer">
        <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This dashboard presents estimates based on
        publicly available data and peer-reviewed research. It is intended to
        illustrate the potential human cost of regulatory delay, not to predict
        exact outcomes. The authors are advocates for autonomous vehicle deployment
        and present this data in good faith to inform public discourse. All
        sources are linked for independent verification. Forked from
        <a href="https://tbhochman.github.io/dc-waymo-dashboard/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DC Waymo Delay Dashboard</a>
        by T. Hochman.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
